{
  "answer": "In Charles Comte's *Traité de la Propriété* (Vol. I), the territorial frame foundational to modern nationalism is treated as an unexamined anthropological given: each human group, from savage hordes to civilized nations, naturally possesses and fiercely defends a bounded \"national territory\" (e.g., a river basin enclosed by mountains), which precedes and enables all lesser properties (individual, communal, provincial).[^1] This is not presented as a construct but as an empirical fact, observed universally across history and ethnography, with natural limits set by geography and subsistence needs; violations provoke existential wars, and it forms the \"highest property\" enclosing all others.[^2]\n\nIqbal's poem most clearly contradicts this in the stanza rejecting confinement to place as calamity, contrasting secular/political nationalism (\"the Nation is but land\")—echoing Comte's naturalized territorial essence—with prophetic Islam, where \"Homeland is by God’s command\" (i.e., universal faith, not delimited earth).[^3]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/07-du-territoire-propre-a-chaque-nation/translation/#p-2cfb18).\n\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de la propriété: VOL I*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-la-propriete-vol-i-2c7a99/10-de-la-conversion-du-territoire-national-en-proprie/translation/#p-6c84d4).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/25-wataniyat/translation/#p-a723b2).",
